Russia debates its future.
JAROSLAWL: Russia, many say, lacks a "civil society".
But it somewhat matches this partly with a rather interesting public space, in which serious issues are indeed debated and where fleeting glimpses of the powerful are not entirely restricted to TV clips.
In the first two weeks of September, there were consecutive meetings of two major Russian political groups, the Valdai Discussion Club and the Global Policy Forum.
The first took place on a ship and ended with a dinner with Prime Minister Vladimir Putin in Sochi on the Black Sea.
This culminated in a symposium in Yaroslavl with President Dmitry Medvedev.
Scientists, think tank members, and journalists (both Russian and foreign) discussed Russia's future with important politicians and business leaders.
Three things made these events uniquely Russian in a way.
The first thing was intense media interest.
Even an extremely camera-shy scientist could suddenly find himself as a Russian TV star.
The second aspect was the willingness of both Putin and Medvedev to publicly engage with experts on their own intellectual turf.
Only one western political leader of recent times comes to mind who had the self-confidence to do this; that was Bill Clinton.
And finally, the two events marked the emergence of two rival political forums, each exuding the faint but unmistakable scent of an escalating conflict.
Those with eyes in their head would have gained an intriguing insight into a crumbling diarchy from these two conferences.
The main theme of the Valdai Conference was whether Russia's history and geography condemned it to authoritarian rule.
If democracy is the future, is it then Russia's fate to miss out?
The pessimists – above all Russian historians – argued that it would be difficult if not impossible for Russia to overcome its autocratic legacy.
Lew Beloussow from Moscow State Lomonosov University argued that autocracy in Russia rises again like a phoenix from the ashes, supported by the passivity and endurance of the Russians.
The Bolsheviks would have inherited the autocracy from the Tsars; Putin rediscovered the old monarchical principle of anointing his successor and thus circumvented the democratic contest for the presidency.
Radicals such as Vladimir Ryschkow repudiated this historical determinism. One should not, Ryschkow argued, legitimise authoritarianism by reference to history.
The protests intensified.
It be the yoke of Putin, not that of history, that weighs heavily on Russia.
Many things in this discussion were lacking in clarity, as tends to be the case in discussions of this kind.
Most participants failed to distinguish between history as limitation and history as determinant.
Countries and civilizations can never fully overcome their history, but every history offers many different possibilities.
Countries are not genetically programmed like animals.
The discussion about autocracy was inevitably linked to other topics.
People defended autocracy in Russia as necessary for an empire.
But this leads to another question: Does Russia need an empire?
Can Russia renounce its imperial past and establish normal relations with its newly independent neighbors, such as Ukraine and Georgia?
Can it really be a completely "normal" actor on the world stage?
At the conference in Yaroslavl with Medvedev, attention shifted to the connection between democracy and modernization.
Everyone agreed that Russia had to diversify its economy and overcome its dependence on energy.
As Medvedev emphasized, an economy based on raw materials is always vulnerable to fluctuations in the prices of raw materials.
However, there are roughly two views on the relationship between political and economic modernization.
Putin's view is that democracy results from a modern economy, as a kind of reward for the hard work done.
If the state drives modernization from the top forward, democracy will grow naturally, albeit slowly, due to increasing prosperity and a growing middle class.
The Kremlin's chief ideologue, Vladislav Surkov, has suggested that a genuine democracy would require a "democracy in the head," implying that the desirable mental state is still far away in Russia.
The alternative view, as represented by people such as Igor Yurgens, the head of Medvedev's preferred think tank, the Institute of Contemporary Development, is that democracy is a prerequisite for economic modernization.
They argue that the Russian state in its current form lacks any genuine incentive for reforming its own poor economic habits – or those of the Russians.
This development so far confirms this.
Russia has a modest recovery from the recession.
However, there is almost no innovation; the elites are content to live a comfortable life with the profits from the energy business, and corruption continues unchecked.
Putin is the strong leader of a weak state, which, lacking a mobilizing element or feedback process, is unable to carry out a modernization project.
There is a clear rift between Putin and Medvedev.
Medvedev is anything but Putin's puppet.
Both believe that democracy must come sooner or later, but with Putin, the emphasis is clearly on "later," while Medvedev has supplemented the public discourse in Russia with a liberating voice.
Skeptics claim that this is merely a misleading routine following the motto "good cop, bad cop".
But words count, and a new rhetoric is a political force in its own right.
Medvedev's main strategic goal must now be to secure a second term as President.
He cannot openly question Putin's legacy, but must position himself as someone who goes beyond Putin.
It's a difficult balancing act, because Putin can take back the presidency at any time if he thinks his former protégé wants to dismantle the authoritarian state that Putin created.
Nineteen years after the fall of communism, Russia's direction remains unclear as ever.
This is most important for the Russians, but because Russia spans the vast Eurasian landmass, the lack of clarity about Russia's future forces the rest of us to be constantly worried.
Is Russia part of the West?
Granting him a history and geography with an unmistakably Eurasian perspective, capable of smoothing out a potential clash between Western and Eastern civilizations or between Christianity and Islam.
Russia cannot be neatly categorized into geopolitical categories, but it remains too important to be ignored.
